FORMAT: 1A
HOST: https://app.seerist.com/hyperionapi/

# Seerist

The Seerist API is a REST based API for Authenticating and querying HotSpot, Pulse and 
Pulse Forecasting data from [Seerist, Inc.](https://seerist.com)

# Allowed HTTPs request

<pre>
GET:   Get a resource, all outputs are in GeoJson format. There will be a metadata section and a features section with properties and a geometry object.
POST:  POST is only used in the Authentication API and will not be needed if you are using x-api-key Header Authentication (API Key vs Bearer Token).
</pre>

# Description of Usual Server Responses:
- 200 `OK` - the request was successful
- 400 `Bad Request` - There was something incorrect about your request, maybe the METHOD was wrong (POST vs GET) or a parameter is incorrect
- 401 `UNAUTHORIZED` - No Valid Bearer Token or API Key was supplied, please use the Auth API to request a new Valid Token or [Contact Us](mailto:help@seerist.com) for an API Key.
- 429 `Too Many Requests` - You have exceeded your quota for the day. Each API key has a daily quota based on the number of API Calls purchased. This quota will reset each day. 

The Seerist API also preforms caching of various resource calls. We control the cache time within our backend and it is
synced with our update schedule. Various algorithms update on a predefined schedule and making the same request 
multiple times in a row will result in the same data being returned. To increase performance we cache these results
and then invalidate the cache as new data becomes available. You can see if you are receiving cached data by inspecting the 
response headers for 'X-Cache' key. A value of 'Miss from cloudfront' indicates the request was NOT cached and you are receiving
the latest data, a value of 'Hit from cloudfront' indicates the opposite and you are receiving cached data.

# Using this documentation and executing Examples

Each method described below contains examples and code samples. You can modify the request parameters within this 
documentation and send the request directly from your browser. To use any of these request you will need to
to obtain an API Key from Seerist first. To use these examples select an API Method and in the Request Headers
find the x-api-key parameter and put the API Key as the value, then select the Call Resource button. 

If you would like code samples from various popular languages (Java, Javascript, Node.js, Ruby, Python and many more) 
swithch back to the Example view (Button in top right). Scroll back to the 'Try' button and change the Raw dropdown
to the language you'd like examples from.

# Group Authentication

All request require Authentication, the primary way to Authenticate to the SeeristAPI is via an x-api-key Header. These API keys are sutiable for use on
desktop applications and server side code. They are issued and are expired manually. Because of this
it is important to not share the API key or place it in any publically visible place. Due to the 
simplistic nature of the x-api-key they can only access generic data, no personal data (like alerts). If
you wish to use an x-api-key Seerist will provide you with one and you will pass it on as an additional
header parameter (x-api-key).

Here is an example cURL using your x-api-key. Replace API_KEY_HERE with the API Key provided by Seerist.UR

<pre>
curl --location --request GET 'https://app.seerist.com/hyperionapi/v2/pulse/country' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'x-api-key: API_KEY_HERE'
</pre>


# Group Hotspots

Hotspots alert you to sudden dangerous events taking place worldwide. Hotspots are triggered by a combination of high activity 
levels and Events. Hotspots is a machine learning model that monitors activity levels across the globe. When activity spikes, 
this triggers a Hotspot that notifies the user that they may need to look into the events taking place in that area. 

Both Abi and Matt use Hotspots daily. This is how: 
 - Every morning, Abi logs into Seerist and uses Hotspots worldwide to quickly determine if activity levels have peaked near her 
   global offices. Abi also created alerts so she can be notified of any new Hotspots that trigger in the vicinity of her offices. 
 - On a daily basis, Matt also zooms to the countries/cities his clients are in or traveling to and uses Hotspots to quickly 
   determine if any dangerous events have occurred, or are occurring, that could hinder their travel. 

The Hotspots API will return a list of Hotspots with various properties, one of those properties will be clusterIds. In order to retrieve the articles associated with a hotspot you will need to query the [World of Data](#reference/world-of-data) endpoint with the cluster id, i.e. v1/wod?clusterId={clusterId}.
    
## All HotSpots by Bounds/AoiId [/v1/hotspots{?bounds,aoiId,start,end,pageSize,pageOffset}]

Allows you to query hotspots by a bounding geometry or AOI ID and returns all hotspots in Seerist.

+ Parameters
    + bounds : `-7.03,3.80,41.53,71.06` (string, optional) - Contains the southwest and northeast lat/lon coordinates of the bounding box corners with format SWLat,SWLon,NELat,NELon, e.g. -7.03,3.80,41.53,71.06
    + `aoiId` : us (string, optional) - AOI Identifier to limit the results from, this can be a GeoHash value, 2 Letter Country Code or City Code
    + start : `2019-01-22T00:00:00.000Z` (string, optional) - Start of the date (and optionally time) interval, e.g. 2016-09-15T00:00:00.000
    + end : `2019-01-22T23:59:59.999Z` (string, optional) - End of the date (and optionally time) interval, e.g. 2016-09-20T23:59:59.999
    + pageSize : 100 (numeric, optional) - Number of Records to include in the response  
    + pageOffset : 0 (numeric, optional) - Number of Records to offset in the request, used in conjunction with pageSize to retrieve all records

### All HotSpots by Bounds [GET]
+ Request (application/json)
    + Headers
        
            x-api-key: xxxx
      
+ Response 200 (application/json)
    + Attributes (HotSpotBounds Response)  

## Top Hotspots by Bounds/AoiId [/v1/hotspots/topic/top{?bounds,aoiId,start,end,pageSize,pageOffset}]

Returns only the Top Hotspots Related Hotspots by a bounding geomatry or AOI ID

+ Parameters
    + bounds : `-7.03,3.80,41.53,71.06` (string, optional) - Contains the southwest and northeast lat/lon coordinates of the bounding box corners with format SWLat,SWLon,NELat,NELon, e.g. -7.03,3.80,41.53,71.06
    + `aoiId` : us (string, optional) - AOI Identifier to limit the results from, this can be a GeoHash value, 2 Letter Country Code or City Code
    + start : `2019-01-22T00:00:00.000Z` (string, optional) - Start of the date (and optionally time) interval, e.g. 2016-09-15T00:00:00.000
    + end : `2019-01-22T23:59:59.999Z` (string, optional) - End of the date (and optionally time) interval, e.g. 2016-09-20T23:59:59.999
    + pageSize : 100 (numeric, optional) - Number of Records to include in the response  
    + pageOffset : 0 (numeric, optional) - Number of Records to offset in the request, used in conjunction with pageSize to retrieve all records

### Top HotSpots by Bounds [GET]
+ Request (application/json)
    + Headers
        
            x-api-key: xxxx
      
+ Response 200 (application/json)
    + Attributes (HotSpotBounds Response)
    
