# Group Pulse    
    
Pulse allows you to take the pulse of the world anywhere, anytime. Just like doctors take our pulse to assess our general health status, 
Seerist takes the world’s pulse to determine its health, considering factors such as stability and risk.

Pulse monitors the entire world at four different area levels (country, region, city, and county) and, for each level, produces real time,
constantly-updating stability assessments. Pulse monitors the entire world and produce real time stability assessments.

This is what the colors mean for Pulse:
 - If Kandahar is Dark Green, this means it’s a very stable place;
 - If Kandahar is Light Green, this means it’s a stable place;
 - If Kandahar is YELLOW, this means it’s a slightly unstable place;
 - If Kandahar is ORANGE, this means it’s an unstable place;
 - If Kandahar is RED, this means it’s a very unstable place.

Both Abi and Matt use Pulse on a daily basis. This is how: 
 - Abi uses Pulse to monitor the stability conditions in and around her company’s global offices. With a few minutes and a handful of clicks, 
   Pulse allows her to rapidly review the stability conditions of every country and city in which her company has offices and examine the stability 
   forecast for the next week. With Pulse she detects and monitors downward stability trends that could, over time, create unstable conditions 
   for her employees. With Pulse she detects stability changes that diverge from the usual trends of those areas. To ensure she doesn’t 
   miss anything, Abi also created Pulse alerts around every office so she can be notified of any sudden Pulse changes. 
 - Matt uses Pulse on a regular basis to check the stability conditions of European cities his clients travel to. Pulse allows him to 
   continuously monitor the cities, look for decreasing stability trends, and catch a glimpse of the forecast to determine if the recent stability 
   trends are expected to persist into next week. Pulse allows him to determine whether there have been any sudden stability changes out of 
   norm for that area that could jeopardize his client’s travel plans.     
    
## Pulse Region by Bounds [/v2/pulse/region{?model,bounds,start,end,pageSize,pageOffset,sortField,sortDirection,includeForecast}]

Allows you to query Pulse at the region level by Bounding Geometry. Regions are defined as Geohash Level 3 Grids. 

+ Parameters
    + model: `v2` (string, optional) - Selection of scoring model for Pulse
        + Members
            + v1
            + v2
        + Default: v1
    + bounds : `-7.03,3.80,41.53,71.06` (string, optional) - Contains the southwest and northeast lat/lon coordinates of the bounding box corners with format SWLat,SWLon,NELat,NELon, e.g. -7.03,3.80,41.53,71.06
    + start : `2019-01-22T00:00:00.000Z` (string, optional) - Start of the date (and optionally time) interval, e.g. 2016-09-15T00:00:00.000
    + end : `2019-01-22T23:59:59.999Z` (string, optional) - End of the date (and optionally time) interval, e.g. 2016-09-20T23:59:59.999
    + pageSize : 100 (numeric, optional) - Number of events to include in the response  
    + pageOffset : 0 (numeric, optional) - Number of Records to offset in the request, used in conjunction with pageSize to retrieve all records
    + sortField : startTime (string, optional) - The result field to sort the FeatureCollection Properties on
        + Members
            + geohash
            + count
            + score
            + startTime
        + Default: startTime
    + sortDirection : desc (string, optional) - Ascending or Descending
        + Members
            + asc
            + desc
        + Default: desc
    + includeForecast : false (bool, optional) - Flag if forcast values should also be included        

### Pulse Region by Bounds [GET]
+ Request (application/json)
    + Headers
        
            x-api-key: xxxx
      
+ Response 200 (application/json)
    + Attributes (Pulse Response Region)
    
